1. What a category is

A category has two things:
	1.	Objects
	2.	Morphisms (arrows / relationships between objects)

Example:

A  ──f──▶  B

	•	A and B are objects
	•	f is a transformation between them.

The important part: the relationships are primary, not the objects.

That’s already very Pantheon-like.

⸻

2. Now the wild idea: a functor

A functor is a mapping between entire categories.

Meaning:

Category 1         Category 2
   A  ─f→  B   →      F(A) ─F(f)→ F(B)

A functor translates:
	•	objects → objects
	•	relationships → relationships.

But it preserves structure.

So the relationships stay valid after translation.

⸻

3. Real-world example

Physics uses this constantly.

Example translation:

Domain	Object	Relationship
mechanics	position	velocity
thermodynamics	energy	entropy
finance	price	volatility

The equations often stay structurally identical.

This is why one equation can appear in:
	•	heat diffusion
	•	stock models
	•	population dynamics
	•	particle physics.

The structure survived the translation.

That’s a functorial mapping.

